    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1969-10-29T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1969-10-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="154"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d154">
                <head>154. Memorandum From <persName corresp="#p_GMA1" type="from">Michael
                        Guhin</persName> of the National Security Council Staff to the President’s
                    Assistant for National Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_KHA1" type="to"
                        >Kissinger</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d154fn1">Source:
                        National Archives, Nixon Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> Files, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Institutional
                        Files (H-Files), Box H–40, Review Group Meeting, <gloss target="#t_NSSM1"
                            >NSSM</gloss> 59, <gloss target="#t_CW1">CW</gloss> and <gloss
                            target="#t_BW1">BW</gloss>, 10/30/69. Top Secret. Sent for
                        information.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d154fn2">In this memorandum, <persName
                            corresp="#p_GMA1">Guhin</persName> discussed the Talking Points prepared
                        on <gloss target="#t_CBW1">CBW</gloss> for <persName corresp="#p_KHA1"
                            >Kissinger</persName> for the upcoming <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> Review Group meeting. He then attached an outline of
                        probable agency positions on the various policy issues.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1969-10-29"
                        >October 29, 1969</date>
                </dateline>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT:</head>
                    <item>Specific Issues and Agency Positions</item>
                </list>
                <p>Your “Talking Points” deal only with Part II (“<gloss target="#t_CW1">CW</gloss>
                    and <gloss target="#t_BW1">BW</gloss> Policy Issues”) of the <gloss
                        target="#t_IPMG1">IPMG</gloss> report as Part I is background information
                    only. Your “Talking Points” simply (1) re-phrase the specific issue where
                    appropriate; (2) highlight the principal issues in each basic policy
                    consideration while attempting to point out the interrelationships between these
                    issues; (3) emphasize various pro and con points of consideration under each
                    issue; and (4) stress the point that consideration should be focused upon these
                    three broad policy areas:</p>
                <list>
                    <item>Policy on Biological Warfare</item>
                    <item>Policy on Chemical Warfare</item>
                    <item>Policy on Geneva Protocol and the Use of Tear Gas and/or
                        Herbicides.</item>
                </list>
                <p>There are no substantive differences between the issues highlighted in your
                    “Talking Points” and in the <gloss target="#t_IPMG1">IPMG</gloss> paper—merely
                    differences in structuring and <hi rend="underline">emphasis.</hi>
                </p>
                <p>Your “Talking Points” also mention that <gloss target="#t_OST1">OST</gloss> will
                    raise another issue, (which we agree should be addressed): “Should the use in
                    war of tear gases and herbicides require Presidential authorization?” (This
                    issue can be added to the <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss>
                    <gloss target="#t_CW1">CW</gloss>–<gloss target="#t_BW1">BW</gloss> agenda for
                    discussion.)</p>
                <p>Attached is a list of the specific issues under the headings as they stand in the
                        <gloss target="#t_IPMG1">IPMG</gloss> report along with probable agency
                    positions. On most of the specific issues, we do not know <gloss
                        target="#t_CIA1">CIA</gloss>’s position. <gloss target="#t_CIA1">CIA</gloss>
                    is therefore included only when their position appears obvious.</p>
                <pb facs="d154-02" n="2" xml:id="d154-02"/>
                <frus:attachment>
                    <head>Attachment</head>
                    <p rend="center">
                        <hi rend="underline">ISSUES AND AGENCY POSITIONS</hi>
                        <note n="*" xml:id="d154fn3">Positions based on opinions expressed in <gloss
                                target="#t_IPMG1">IPMG</gloss> and Working Group sessions.</note>
                    </p>
                    <p>I. <hi rend="underline">
                            <gloss target="#t_CW1">CW</gloss> Policy Issues</hi>
                    </p>
                    <p>A. Should the U.S. maintain a capability to employ lethal chemical
                        agents?</p>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="underline">Agencies For</hi>: <gloss target="#t_OSD1">OSD</gloss>,
                        State, <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_OST1"
                            >OST</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_CIA1">CIA</gloss>, <gloss
                            target="#t_USIA1">USIA</gloss>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="underline">Agencies Against:</hi>
                        <gloss target="#t_ACDA1">ACDA</gloss> (?)</p>
                    <p>B. Should the U.S. continue to maintain stockpiles of chemical munitions
                        overseas (1) in Europe, and (2) in the Pacific?</p>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="underline">Agencies For Europe Stocks:</hi>
                        <gloss target="#t_OSD1">OSD</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss>,
                            <gloss target="#t_OST1">OST</gloss>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="underline">Agencies Possibly Against Europe Stocks:</hi> State,
                            <gloss target="#t_ACDA1">ACDA</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_USIA1"
                            >USIA</gloss>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="underline">Agencies for Pacific Stocks:</hi>
                        <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="underline">Agencies Against Pacific Stocks:</hi>
                        <gloss target="#t_OSD1">OSD</gloss>, State, <gloss target="#t_ACDA1"
                            >ACDA</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_USIA1">USIA</gloss>
                    </p>
                    <p>C. Should the U.S. preserve a first-use option for incapacitating
                        chemicals?</p>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="underline">Agencies For:</hi>
                        <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_OSD1"
                        >OSD</gloss>:(?)</p>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="underline">Agencies Against:</hi> State, <gloss target="#t_ACDA1"
                            >ACDA</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_OST1">OST</gloss>, <gloss
                            target="#t_USIA1">USIA</gloss>
                    </p>
                    <p>D. Should the U.S. maintain an option for unrestricted use of riot control
                        agents (tear gas) in warfare and continue exercising this option in
                        Vietnam?</p>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="underline">Agencies For:</hi>
                        <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_OSD1">OSD</gloss>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="underline">Agencies Against:</hi> State (?), <gloss
                            target="#t_ACDA1">ACDA</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_OST1">OST</gloss>,
                            <gloss target="#t_USIA1">USIA</gloss>
                    </p>
                    <p>E. If the U.S. maintains an option to use tear gas in war, should it be
                        limited to “humanitarian purposes”?</p>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="underline">Agencies For:</hi> State (?), <gloss target="#t_ACDA1"
                            >ACDA</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_OST1">OST</gloss>, <gloss
                            target="#t_USIA1">USIA</gloss>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="underline">Agencies Against:</hi>
                        <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_OSD1">OSD</gloss>
                    </p>
                    <pb facs="d154-03" n="3" xml:id="d154-03"/>
                    <p>F. Should the U.S. retain a policy permitting first-use of chemical
                        herbicides?</p>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="underline">Agencies For:</hi>
                        <gloss target="#t_OSD1">OSD</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss>,
                        State (?)</p>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="underline">Agencies Against:</hi>
                        <gloss target="#t_ACDA1">ACDA</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_USIA1">USIA</gloss>
                    </p>
                    <p>II. <hi rend="underline">
                            <gloss target="#t_BW1">BW</gloss> Policy Issues</hi>
                    </p>
                    <p>A. Should the U.S. maintain a lethal biological capability beyond research,
                        development and testing?</p>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="underline">Agencies For</hi>: <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="underline">Agencies Against:</hi>
                        <gloss target="#t_OSD1">OSD</gloss>, State, <gloss target="#t_ACDA1"
                            >ACDA</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_OST1">OST</gloss>, <gloss
                            target="#t_USIA1">USIA</gloss>
                    </p>
                    <p>B. Should the U.S. maintain a capability for use of incapacitating
                        biologicals?</p>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="underline">Agencies For:</hi>
                        <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="underline">Agencies Against:</hi>
                        <gloss target="#t_OSD1">OSD</gloss>, State, <gloss target="#t_ACDA1"
                            >ACDA</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_OST1">OST</gloss>, <gloss
                            target="#t_USIA1">USIA</gloss>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <note n="**" xml:id="d154fn4">These three policy options in the <gloss
                                target="#t_IPMG1">IPMG</gloss> report boil down to the fact that
                                <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_OSD1"
                                >OSD</gloss> favor unrestricted use of tear gas in wartime, State’s
                            position is unresolved, and <gloss target="#t_ACDA1">ACDA</gloss>,
                                <gloss target="#t_USIA1">USIA</gloss> and OST do not favor
                            unrestricted use of tear gas.</note> III. <hi rend="underline">Geneva
                            Protocol Issue</hi>
                    </p>
                    <p>A. Should the U.S. ratify the Geneva Protocol of 1925 with either a
                        reservation or an interpretative statement permitting the U.S. to use
                        chemical and biological incapacitating agents, tear gas, and other
                        non-lethal agents in wartime without restriction?</p>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="underline">Agencies For:</hi>
                        <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="underline">Agencies Against:</hi>
                        <gloss target="#t_OSD1">OSD</gloss> (?), State, <gloss target="#t_ACDA1"
                            >ACDA</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_OST1">OST</gloss>, <gloss
                            target="#t_USIA1">USIA</gloss>
                    </p>
                    <p>B. Should the U.S. ratify the Geneva Protocol with a reservation or
                        interpretative statement permitting the U.S. to use <hi rend="underline"
                            >tear gas</hi> in wartime <hi rend="underline">without
                            restrictions?</hi>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="underline">Agencies For:</hi>
                        <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_OSD1">OSD</gloss>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="underline">Agencies Against:</hi> State (?), <gloss
                            target="#t_ACDA1">ACDA</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_USIA1">USIA</gloss>,
                            <gloss target="#t_OST1">OST</gloss>
                    </p>
                    <pb facs="d154-04" n="4" xml:id="d154-04"/>
                    <p>C. Should the U.S. ratify the Geneva Protocol with a reservation or
                        interpretative statement to the effect that the U.S. does not view the
                        Protocol as prohibiting the use of <hi rend="underline">riot control
                            agents</hi> in wartime for <hi rend="underline">humanitarian
                            purposes?</hi>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="underline">Agencies For:</hi> State, <gloss target="#t_ACDA1"
                            >ACDA</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_USIA1">USIA</gloss>, <gloss
                            target="#t_OST1">OST</gloss>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="underline">Agencies Against:</hi>
                        <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_OSD1">OSD</gloss>
                    </p>
                </frus:attachment>
            </div>
        </body>
